1. Install Docker
First, make sure Docker is installed on your system. You can download it from docker.com for Windows, Mac, or Linux.
2. Pull an Image
Containers are created from images. To get an image from Docker Hub:
bashdocker pull ubuntu
3. Run a Container
The simplest way to create and start a container:
bashdocker run -it ubuntu
This creates a container from the ubuntu image and starts an interactive terminal session.
Common Options
When running containers, you'll often use these flags:

-d — Run in detached mode (background)
-p — Map ports (e.g., -p 8080:80 maps host port 8080 to container port 80)
--name — Give your container a specific name
-v — Mount volumes for persistent data
-e — Set environment variables

Example with options:
bashdocker run -d --name my-nginx -p 8080:80 nginx
This runs an nginx web server in the background, names it "my-nginx", and makes it accessible on port 8080.
Managing Containers
bashdocker ps                  # List running containers
docker ps -a              # List all containers
docker stop my-nginx      # Stop a container
docker start my-nginx     # Start a stopped container
docker rm my-nginx        # Remove a container
Using a Dockerfile
For custom containers, create a Dockerfile:
dockerfileFROM ubuntu:latest
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y python3
COPY app.py /app/
WORKDIR /app
CMD ["python3", "app.py"]
Then build and run:
bashdocker build -t my-app .
docker run my-app
Is there a specific type of container or application you're looking to set up?
